The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, January 15, 2004 				 AllBank to buy 10% in UTIs asset recast firm
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								Calcutta, Jan. 14: Allahabad Bank is picking up a 10 per cent stake in ASERC, an asset reconstruction company floated by UTI Mutual Fund.																								Addressing a press conference here today, chairman and managing director . . Singh said, The board of directors has decided to take a 10 per cent stake in ASERC, which is going to be launched by the end of this month. The capital base of the asset reconstruction company is Rs 5 crore.																								Life Insurance Corporation of India will also pick up a 10 per cent stake in ASERC.																								The bank today announced a 115 per cent increase in its third-quarter net profit at Rs 98.36 crore against Rs 45.75 crore in the corresponding previous period.																								The bank also decided to sell UTI Mutual Fund schemes from its branches to increase it fee-based income and utilise excess staff, Singh said, adding that a formal memorandum would be signed soon.																								Earlier, the bank had tied up with National Insurance Corporation and ICICI Prudential Life Insurance to sell their general and life insurance policies respectively.																								The board also took a final call on the setting up of the offshore banking unit (OBU) at Noida. It will be our first breakthrough to start operations outside the country. Once it is established, in another three months we may set up international branches, Singh said.																								Asked whether the bank would increase its stake in UTIs asset reconstruction company in future, the Singh said, It depends on opportunity whether we will increase our stake in future.																								The banks operating profit during the nine month period of the current fiscal increased 41.88 per cent to Rs 556.08 crore from Rs 391.94 crore while net profit surged 119.70 per cent to Rs 242.24 crore from Rs 110.26 crore in the corresponding previous period.																								During the third quarter, operating profit increased 32.32 per cent to Rs 235.42 crore from Rs 177.92 crore in the previous corresponding period.																								In the third quarter, the banks gross NPA came down to below 10 per cent to 9.8 per cent as on December, 2003, while net NPA came down to 4.17 per cent from 8.28 per cent in December, 2002. The bank is sure of bring it down to below 4 per cent by March, 2004.
